## Tutanota Codebase Exploration: Mail Architecture and Session Key Management

Based on my thorough exploration of the Tutanota codebase, here's a comprehensive breakdown of the five key areas you requested:

---

## 1. Mail Entity Structure and Loading

**Mail Entity Definition** (`/app/src/api/entities/tutanota/TypeRefs.ts`, lines 1211-1255):

```typescript
export type Mail = {
  _type: TypeRef<Mail>;
  _errors: Object;
  _format: NumberString;
  _id: IdTuple;                      // [folderId, mailId]
  _ownerEncSessionKey: null | Uint8Array;
  _ownerGroup: null | Id;
  _permissions: Id;
  authStatus: null | NumberString;
  confidential: boolean;
  differentEnvelopeSender: null | string;
  listUnsubscribe: boolean;
  method: NumberString;
  movedTime: null | Date;
  phishingStatus: NumberString;
  receivedDate: Date;
  recipientCount: NumberString;
  replyType: NumberString;
  sentDate: null | Date;
  state: NumberString;
  subject: string;
  unread: boolean;

  attachments: IdTuple[];
  bccRecipients: MailAddress[];
  body: null | Id;                  // Legacy: direct MailBody reference
  bucketKey: null | BucketKey;      // New permission model: contains session keys
  ccRecipients: MailAddress[];
  conversationEntry: IdTuple;
  firstRecipient: null | MailAddress;
  headers: null | Id;
  mailDetails: null | IdTuple;       // New model: details blob reference
  mailDetailsDraft: null | IdTuple;  // New model: draft details reference
  replyTos: EncryptedMailAddress[];  // Legacy model
  restrictions: null | MailRestriction;
  sender: MailAddress;
  toRecipients: MailAddress[];       // Legacy model
}
```

**Mail Loading Patterns** (`/app/src/mail/model/MailUtils.ts`, lines 397-408):

The `loadMailDetails()` function handles three scenarios:

```typescript
export async function loadMailDetails(entityClient: EntityClient, mail: Mail): Promise<MailWrapper> {
  if (isLegacyMail(mail)) {
    // Legacy: Load MailBody directly via mail.body reference
    return entityClient.load(MailBodyTypeRef, neverNull(mail.body))
      .then((b) => MailWrapper.body(mail, b))
  } else if (isDetailsDraft(mail)) {
    // New model: Load MailDetailsDraft for draft emails
    return entityClient.load(MailDetailsDraftTypeRef, neverNull(mail.mailDetailsDraft))
      .then((d) => MailWrapper.details(mail, d.details))
  } else {
    // New model: Load MailDetailsBlob for received/sent emails
    const mailDetailsId = neverNull(mail.mailDetails)
    return entityClient
      .loadMultiple(MailDetailsBlobTypeRef, listIdPart(mailDetailsId), [elementIdPart(mailDetailsId)])
      .then((d) => MailWrapper.details(mail, d[0].details))
  }
}
```

---

## 2. Session Key Management and Storage

**Key Concepts:**

Session keys are stored in multiple locations depending on the permission model:

### Legacy Permission Model (Pre-Blob Migration)
- **_ownerEncSessionKey**: Encrypted with the owning group's key
- **Location**: On the Mail entity itself
- **Decryption**: `decryptKey(ownerGroupKey, _ownerEncSessionKey)`

### New Permission Model (Bucket-based)
- **bucketKey**: An aggregate containing encrypted session keys for multiple entities
- **BucketKey structure** (`/app/src/api/entities/sys/TypeRefs.ts`, lines 454-463):

```typescript
export type BucketKey = {
  _type: TypeRef<BucketKey>;
  _id: Id;
  groupEncBucketKey: null | Uint8Array;     // Encrypted with group key
  pubEncBucketKey: null | Uint8Array;       // Encrypted with public key
  bucketEncSessionKeys: InstanceSessionKey[];  // Array of instance session keys
  keyGroup: null | Id;                      // Group used for encryption
}
```

### InstanceSessionKey Structure
```typescript
export type InstanceSessionKey = {
  _type: TypeRef<InstanceSessionKey>;
  _id: Id;
  instanceId: Id;           // The ID of the entity (e.g., MailDetailsBlob ID)
  instanceList: Id;         // The list containing the instance
  symEncSessionKey: Uint8Array;  // The encrypted session key
  typeInfo: TypeInfo;       // Type information
}
```

**Session Key Cache** (`/app/src/api/worker/crypto/CryptoFacade.ts`, lines 80-84):

```typescript
export class CryptoFacade {
  // Caches session keys by element ID to optimize performance
  private readonly sessionKeyCache: Record<string, Aes128Key> = {}

  // Used for Mail and MailBody (they share the same session key)
  // Also optimizes performance when loading MailDetails
}
```

---

## 3. Entity Loading and Decryption

**EntityRestClient Flow** (`/app/src/api/worker/rest/EntityRestClient.ts`, lines 114-147):

1. **Load from server** (HTTP GET)
2. **Apply migrations** (handle schema changes)
3. **Resolve session key** using one of these strategies:
   - From cache (if already loaded)
   - From bucketKey (new permission model)
   - From _ownerEncSessionKey (if user is in owner group)
   - From Permission objects (legacy public/external permissions)
4. **Decrypt and map** to instance using InstanceMapper
5. **Cache** session key for related entities

**Session Key Resolution Hierarchy** (`/app/src/api/worker/crypto/CryptoFacade.ts`, lines 193-250):

```typescript
resolveSessionKey(typeModel: TypeModel, instance: Record<string, any>): Promise<Aes128Key | null> {
  1. Check sessionKeyCache
  2. If bucketKey exists:
     - Decrypt bucketKey
     - Extract appropriate session key for this instance
  3. Else if _ownerEncSessionKey exists AND user is in ownerGroup:
     - Decrypt with owner group key
  4. Else if ownerEncSessionKey exists (service instances):
     - Decrypt with mail group key
  5. Else:
     - Load Permission entities
     - Try symmetric permission first
     - Fall back to public/external permission with BucketPermission
}
```

**InstanceMapper Decryption** (`/app/src/api/worker/crypto/InstanceMapper.ts`, lines 24-83):

- Iterates through all model values
- Decrypts each encrypted field using the session key
- Handles aggregations recursively
- Stores encrypted values for later updates (_finalEncrypted_ and _defaultEncrypted_)

---

## 4. Legacy vs. Non-Legacy Permission Models

**Identification** (`/app/src/api/common/MailWrapper.ts`, lines 110-116):

```typescript
export function isLegacyMail(mail: Mail): boolean {
  return mail.mailDetails == null && mail.mailDetailsDraft == null
}

export function isDetailsDraft(mail: Mail): boolean {
  return mail.mailDetailsDraft != null
}
```

### Legacy Model Characteristics:
- Mail contains `body: null | Id` (direct reference to MailBody)
- Mail contains recipient and reply-to info directly
- Uses traditional Permission-based encryption
- MailBody is encrypted with same key as Mail

### New Model Characteristics:
- Mail contains `bucketKey: BucketKey` (contains session keys for multiple entities)
- Mail contains `mailDetails: IdTuple` or `mailDetailsDraft: IdTuple`
- Details are stored in MailDetailsBlob or MailDetailsDraft
- Recipients and reply-tos moved to MailDetails

**Permission Types** (`/app/src/api/common/TutanotaConstants.ts`, lines 63-76):

```typescript
export const enum PermissionType {
  Public = "0",              // Multiple recipients with public key encryption
  Symmetric = "1",           // Another group's symmetric encryption
  Public_Symmetric = "2",    // Updating public with symmetric
  Unencrypted = "3",         // For reference counting (MailBody, FileData)
  External = "5",            // External user permissions
  Owner_List = "8",          // List owner marker
}

export const enum BucketPermissionType {
  Public = "2",              // Public key encryption
  External = "3",            // External user access
}
```

**Permission Resolution Flow** (`/app/src/api/worker/crypto/CryptoFacade.ts`, lines 358-385):

```typescript
// For legacy mails without ownerEncSessionKey, load Permission entities
const permissions = await this.entityClient.loadAll(PermissionTypeRef, instance._permissions)

// Try symmetric permission first (optimized path)
return this.trySymmetricPermission(permissions) ?? 
       (await this.resolveWithPublicOrExternalPermission(permissions, instance, typeModel))
```

---

## 5. Reply-To Addresses and Mail Body Loading

**Reply-To Structure**:

### Legacy Mail:
```typescript
// Stored on Mail entity directly
replyTos: EncryptedMailAddress[];  // Line 1251 of TypeRefs.ts
```

### New Model:
```typescript
// Moved to MailDetails
type MailDetails = {
  _type: TypeRef<MailDetails>;
  _id: Id;
  authStatus: NumberString;
  sentDate: Date;
  body: Body;                      // The mail body
  headers: null | Header;
  recipients: Recipients;
  replyTos: EncryptedMailAddress[];  // Encrypted reply-to addresses
}
```

**Mail Body Access via MailWrapper** (`/app/src/api/common/MailWrapper.ts`):

```typescript
export class MailWrapper {
  getReplyTos(): EncryptedMailAddress[] {
    if (isLegacy(this.details)) {
      return this.mail.replyTos              // From Mail entity
    } else {
      return this.details.details.replyTos   // From MailDetails
    }
  }

  getMailBodyText(): string {
    if (isLegacy(this.details)) {
      return this.details.body.compressedText ?? this.details.body.text ?? ""
    } else {
      return this.details.details.body.compressedText ?? this.details.details.body.text ?? ""
    }
  }
}
```

**Body Structure** (`/app/src/api/entities/tutanota/TypeRefs.ts`, lines 38-50):

```typescript
export type Body = {
  _type: TypeRef<Body>;
  _id: Id;
  compressedText: null | string;    // Compressed mail body
  text: null | string;              // Uncompressed mail body
}

export type MailBody = {
  _type: TypeRef<MailBody>;
  _errors: Object;
  _area: NumberString;
  _format: NumberString;
  _id: Id;
  _owner: Id;
  _ownerEncSessionKey: null | Uint8Array;
  _ownerGroup: null | Id;
  _permissions: Id;
  compressedText: null | string;
  text: null | string;
}
```

**Body Loading in MailViewerViewModel** (`/app/src/mail/view/MailViewerViewModel.ts`, lines 540):

```typescript
private async loadMailDetails(): Promise<MailWrapper> {
  return loadMailDetails(this.entityClient, this.mail)
}

getMailBody(): string {
  if (this.mailWrapper == null) {
    return ""
  }
  return this.mailWrapper.getMailBodyText()
}
```

